#chap-header("3", [= The Dump Site], "Where the bodies are left")

The dump site is where Šauhahten disposes of the bodies after extracting
their souls. It is one of two field locations the party can discover during
exploration; the other is the ritual site. They can be found in either
order --- finding one makes finding the other easier, as trails connect
them.

== Getting There

The surviving peacekeeper's directions point the party northeast of Keshto,
into the thinning Weald where the Fog boundary draws close. The journey
takes the better part of a day on foot --- long enough to feel the
transition from settled land to wilderness.

#flavor[
  The forest changes as you move northeast. The canopy thins. The
  underbrush grows sparser but stranger --- pale shoots, fungi that should
  not grow this far from the Fog. The birdsong stops before you notice it
  has stopped. The air takes on a faint chemical tang that does not belong
  to any forest.
]

#attention[
  *Fog exposure:* The dump site is near the Fog boundary. The party is not
  yet in Dense Fog, but the proximity should be felt --- strange growth,
  unusual silence, the occasional wisp of Fog curling between the trees.
  If any mortal party members are present, note that prolonged exposure in
  this area is unpleasant but not yet mechanically dangerous. The ritual
  site is closer to the Fog and may trigger exposure rules.
]

The peacekeeper's directions give the party the right _area_, not the
right _location_. The ravine is screened by deadfall and brush --- it does
not announce itself. Finding it requires tracking through the thinning
Weald, reading the terrain, and following the signs of repeated passage.

=== Running the Tracking Challenge

The party makes a series of group checks to locate the dump site. Each
stretch represents a section of the Weald that must be searched or
reasoned through.

*Number of stretches:* Start with 2. Each failed check adds 1 additional
stretch (to a maximum of 3 total). Each successful check reduces the
remaining stretches by 1.

*Available checks (each stretch, choose one):*
- *Awareness D3:* Read the terrain --- broken branches at a consistent
  height, undergrowth trampled in a line, pale fungi that cluster along
  a path of disturbed soil. Something has passed this way many times.
- *Investigate D3:* Reason out the disposal logic. The perpetrator needs
  a location screened from casual observation, far enough from Keshto to
  avoid discovery, accessible from a specific direction, and near the Fog
  boundary for cover. That narrows the search to ravines and depressions
  in a specific corridor of the Weald.
- *Stamina D4:* The terrain is rough and the Fog makes it worse ---
  headaches, mild disorientation, a persistent sense of being watched.
  Push through the discomfort to stay on the trail when others would
  turn back.

*Preparation bonus:* If the party got detailed directions from the
surviving peacekeeper in Phase 1 (specifically, if they asked about
landmarks and terrain features), reduce all DCs by 1.

*Complications on failure:*
- The party follows the wrong drainage channel and wastes an hour
  searching a dead-end ravine. Lose time --- if it matters narratively, this
  means they arrive at the dump site closer to dusk.
- A party member loses their footing on a loose scree slope. *Athletics D3*
  to catch themselves; on a failure, they take 3 damage from the fall and
  are Prone at the bottom.
- The party blunders into the Fog-Touched Beast's hunting ground. If
  combat occurs at the dump site later, the beast has already spotted
  them --- it does not arrive as a flanker but is present from the start,
  lurking at the top of the east slope.

#note[
  *Pacing:* This challenge should take 5--10 minutes of real play time.
  Describe each stretch briefly --- a fork in the terrain, a choice of
  direction, a moment of doubt --- call for the check, narrate the result,
  and move on. If the party has the preparation bonus, this should resolve
  in two quick checks and feel rewarding. If they do not, the third
  stretch gives them one more chance without dragging.

  If the party is backtracking a trail from the ritual site, skip this
  challenge entirely --- the trail is clear and consistent.
]

== The Scene

The ravine lies in a fold of the Weald's foothills where a seasonal
stream has cut a channel through soft stone. It runs roughly
northeast-to-southwest, forty feet long and twenty feet across at its
widest point, narrowing at both ends. The walls are uneven --- fifteen feet
deep on the north side where the stone is sheer, sloping to eight feet on
the south side where the ground has eroded into a rough grade. The
seasonal stream has left a shallow drainage channel running the length of
the floor, dry in summer but muddy after rain.

#aloud[
  You smell it before you see it. Not rot, exactly --- something drier, more
  clinical. The trail leads to a shallow ravine screened by deadfall and
  brush. Someone has piled cut branches over the opening. It is not a
  natural formation.

  Beneath the screen, you find the bodies.

  There are seven of them, laid out in a rough row along the west wall,
  partially covered by a weathered tarp weighed down with stones. They are
  not decomposed --- they are _desiccated_, as if every drop of vitality has
  been wrung from them. Their skin is paper-thin, stretched tight over
  bone. Their eyes are open, and their expressions are not peaceful. They
  look as though something was pulled from them, and they felt every moment
  of it.

  The most recent body is perhaps a week old. The oldest could be months.
  Whatever has been done to them has slowed the normal process of decay to
  almost nothing.
]

=== Terrain Features

The following features are relevant for the combat encounter and for
drawing a map of the location.

- *Deadfall screen (southwest entry):* Cut branches and brush piled over
  the ravine's southwest opening, where the trail from Keshto arrives.
  Provides cover and blocks line of sight from outside. Moving through it
  costs 1 extra square of movement. A character can spend 1 AP to pull
  the screen aside, clearing the entry.

- *East slope game trail:* A narrow animal track descends the east wall of
  the ravine in a switchback. It is the route the Fog-Touched Beast uses
  to enter the area. A character on the game trail has elevation over the
  ravine floor (advantage on ranged attacks downward, disadvantage on
  melee from below). The trail is narrow --- only one Medium creature can
  occupy a given section.

- *Drainage channel:* A shallow, muddy channel running the length of the
  ravine floor. Counts as difficult terrain. Characters who are knocked
  Prone in the channel are also Slowed (save ends) from the clinging mud.

- *Rocky outcrops (north ridgeline):* Tumbled boulders along the top of
  the north wall provide full cover and a vantage point overlooking the
  ravine. Climbing up requires 2 squares of movement or an *Athletics D2*
  check to scramble up quickly (1 square).

- *Body row (west wall):* The seven bodies lie in a rough line along the
  base of the west wall, covered by a tarp. The area around the bodies is
  difficult terrain (uneven ground, loose stones, the tarp itself). This
  is where the soul residue hazard is centred.

- *Northeast cairn:* A small pile of stones marks where a faint trail
  exits the ravine to the northeast, toward the ritual site. Šauhahten
  built this to mark the path for himself. It is not hidden --- just
  unremarkable unless you know what to look for.

- *Dense brush (north slope):* Thick undergrowth on the slope below the
  north ridgeline. Provides concealment but not cover. Moving through
  costs 1 extra square.

== Investigating the Scene

- *Occultism D3:* These bodies have had their souls extracted --- not merely
  killed, but _emptied_. Whatever animating force a living person
  possesses, it has been drawn out by deliberate means. This is not the
  work of a predatory creature or a natural Fog phenomenon. Someone did
  this with knowledge and intention.

- *Medicine D4 or Alchemy D4:* The bodies show no signs of conventional
  violence --- no wounds, no poison, no disease. The desiccation is not
  physical dehydration but a side effect of the soul extraction: the body
  collapses inward once the animating principle is removed. The process is
  clean, almost surgical. Whoever did this has performed it many times.

- *Investigate D3:* The disposal is methodical. The bodies were carried
  here, not dragged --- there are no drag marks, but there are faint
  footprints (a single set, returning on the same path each time). The
  ravine was chosen deliberately: screened from casual observation, far
  enough from Keshto to avoid discovery, but accessible from a specific
  direction. The perpetrator comes, deposits a body, and leaves.

- *Awareness D4:* There is a trail leading away from the ravine in a
  direction _different_ from Keshto --- northeast, deeper into the Weald.
  The trail is faint but consistent: the same path used repeatedly. This
  leads to the ritual site. The cairn at the ravine's northeast end
  confirms it --- someone marked this path deliberately.

#note[
  *What this site alone tells the party:*
  - Souls have been extracted from these people.
  - The perpetrator is methodical and has done this many times.
  - The bodies were brought here post-mortem --- this is disposal, not the
    site of the killings.
  - A trail leads deeper into the Weald.

  *What requires both sites:*
  - The full scope of the operation.
  - The method (alchemical, Mortefactor-derived).
  - The fact that neither site is where the perpetrator _lives_.
]

== Field Encounter

Not all the bodies in the row are still. The Fog boundary's proximity and
the residual energy left behind by imperfect soul extraction have done
something to two of the older corpses. They have not been deliberately
reanimated --- Šauhahten does not know they have risen, and would not care
if he did. The Fog seeped in, found empty vessels, and filled them with
just enough to make them move.

#note[
  *When to trigger this encounter:* The husks animate when the party
  enters the ravine and approaches the bodies, or when anyone touches or
  closely examines one of the corpses (i.e. when a character attempts one
  of the investigation checks above). If the party is standing near the
  body row when the husks rise, they are within melee range --- this is
  deliberate. The moment should be shocking.

  If you prefer a less sudden start, have the party notice subtle movement
  under the tarp before the husks fully animate --- an *Awareness D3*
  check to spot it. Characters who succeed are not surprised. Characters
  who fail (or who were not looking) are surprised for the first round.
]

=== Combat: The Risen Dead

*Encounter composition (party of 4):* 2 Soulless Husks (T1 Minion) + 1
Fog-Touched Beast (T1 Standard). Adjust by adding or removing 1 husk for
larger or smaller parties.

The husks rise from the body row. The beast arrives at the top of the east
slope game trail at the start of round 2, drawn by the noise and movement.
If the party blundered into its territory during the tracking challenge,
the beast is already present when combat begins --- it is crouched in the
dense brush on the north slope.

See the Appendix for stat blocks.

#note[
  *Tactical advice:* This is likely the party's first combat in the
  adventure. Run it honestly but simply.

  The husks shamble toward the nearest living creature and attempt to Grab.
  They do not coordinate, do not flank, and do not retreat. They are not
  Šauhahten's controlled servants --- they are empty things driven by
  residual Fog energy. Their movements are jerky and wrong.

  The beast is a predator, not a tactician. It uses Pounce to close
  distance from the game trail, targeting whoever is isolated or already
  Grabbed by a husk. It flees if reduced below half HP --- down the game
  trail and into the Weald.

  *Terrain matters:*
  - A character Grabbed by a husk in the drainage channel is also Slowed
    (mud).
  - The deadfall screen limits escape routes until cleared.
  - The rocky outcrops on the north ridgeline offer a defensible position
    for ranged characters --- but climbing up takes movement.
  - The body row area is difficult terrain, making it hard to manoeuvre
    while the husks are rising around you.
]

*XP:* 7 per Husk + 15 for the Beast = 29 total (for 2 Husks and 1 Beast).

#note[
  *Narrative beat:* This fight should feel _wrong_. The husks are the
  people the party was sent to find. Their faces are recognisable --- the
  missing farmer, the forager's spouse. If the party found the
  peacekeeper's description of the missing in Phase 1, one of the husks
  matches someone on the list.

  The party is fighting the dead they came to avenge. Let the moment land.
  Do not rush past it for the sake of initiative order.
]

== Hazard: Soul Residue

The soul extraction process is not perfectly clean. Fragments of the
victims' essence linger in and around the bodies --- not enough to
constitute a soul, but enough to react when disturbed. This is not a trap
Šauhahten set. It is a byproduct he either does not know about or does
not care about.

#note[
  *When to trigger:* The residue discharges when a character closely
  examines the bodies (any of the Medicine, Alchemy, or Occultism checks
  above) or when the last husk is destroyed and its animating energy
  dissipates back into the remains. Use whichever trigger produces the
  better dramatic moment --- during the investigation if you want to
  interrupt a quiet scene with a jolt, or after the combat if you want a
  final punctuation mark.

  This hazard triggers *once*. After it discharges, the residue is spent.
]

*Effect:* Burst 2 centred on the body row. Every character in the area
must resist with *Grit D3*. On a failure, they take 4 psychic damage
and are Dazed until the end of their next turn. On a success, they feel a
sharp wave of anguish but shake it off --- no damage, no condition.

*Narrative:* A character who fails the resist does not simply take damage.
For a searing instant, they experience a fragment of what the victims
felt: being restrained, something cold and precise pulling at the core of
who they are, a moment of absolute terror as they realise what is
happening, and then --- nothing. Emptiness. The flash passes, leaving a
headache and the certain knowledge that these people were _aware_ when
it happened.

A character who succeeds feels the same anguish at a remove --- like
hearing a scream from another room. Unpleasant, but they can push through
it.

#attention[
  *System lesson for this location:* The dump site teaches three things.

  First, *tracking and exploration* --- the skill challenge demonstrates
  that reaching a destination can itself be a meaningful obstacle, and
  that preparation (talking to the peacekeeper) has mechanical payoff.

  Second, *combat fundamentals* --- the encounter with the husks and the
  beast introduces initiative, terrain, conditions (Grabbed, Slowed), and
  the emotional weight of fighting things that used to be people.

  Third, *environmental hazards* --- the soul residue discharge teaches
  that not all threats are creatures, that supernatural phenomena have
  mechanical teeth, and that the consequences of the villain's work extend
  beyond the immediate crime. If the party skips the investigation and
  focuses only on the combat, the hazard still fires --- gently redirect
  them to the bodies and what they imply.
]
